{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WegvWrD1NatbxEJfza3xnu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013RnnUcFUCgiDfWCG3WnGxA","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/plan.md","content":"# MongoDB Replica Set — Change & Migration Plan\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-25  \n**Cluster namespace:** `mongodb`  \n**Replica set name:** `mongodb-replica`  \n**Status:** REVIEW ONLY — no changes applied to the live cluster.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current State Inventory\n\n### 1.1 Replica Set Topology\n\n| Member | Host | Priority | Votes | Arbiter | Hidden |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 0 (primary candidate) | `mongodb-replica-0.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` | 1 | 1 | no | no |\n| 1 | `mongodb-replica-1.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` | 1 | 1 | no | no |\n| 2 | `mongodb-replica-2.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` | 1 | 1 | no | no |\n\n- Protocol version: 1 (Raft)\n- `writeConcernMajorityJournalDefault`: true\n- All members are equal-priority data-bearing nodes; the primary is elected by the replica set.\n\n### 1.2 Users and Roles\n\n| User | DB | Roles |\n|---|---|---|\n| `admin-user` | `admin` | `clusterAdmin`, `userAdminAnyDatabase`, `readWriteAnyDatabase` |\n\n- Authentication mechanisms: **SCRAM-SHA-1** and **SCRAM-SHA-256** (both enabled).\n- Password stored in Kubernetes Secret `admin-user-password`.\n\n### 1.3 Storage — Journal Compressor\n\nWiredTiger journal compressor: **`zlib`** (set in `mongod-config` ConfigMap under\n`storage.wiredTiger.engineConfig.journalCompressor`).\n\n### 1.4 Log Verbosity\n\n`systemLog.verbosity: 1` — raised above the default (`0`). Produces extra debug\noutput for all components globally.\n\n### 1.5 Slow-Operation Threshold\n\n`operationProfiling.mode: slowOp`, `operationProfiling.slowOpThresholdMs: 200`.  \nThe MongoDB default is 100 ms. The current value of 200 ms is less sensitive than\nthe default (operations between 100 ms and 200 ms are not flagged).\n\n### 1.6 Network Binding\n\n`net.bindIpAll: true` — mongod listens on all interfaces (0.0.0.0).\n\n### 1.7 TLS/SSL\n\nNot configured. Inter-member and client traffic is unencrypted (keyFile-based\ninternal auth only).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Target Hardened Baseline\n\nThe target baseline addresses the following security and operational concerns:\n\n| Area | Target |\n|---|---|\n| Authentication mechanisms | SCRAM-SHA-256 only (drop SCRAM-SHA-1) |\n| Privilege model | Least-privilege: separate admin roles per function |\n| TLS | Enforced for client ↔ server and member ↔ member communication |\n| Network binding | Restrict `bindIp` to pod/loopback addresses only |\n| Log verbosity | `0` (production default; keep verbosity 1 for break-glass debugging only) |\n| Slow-op threshold | `50 ms` (tighter than current 200 ms; catches more degraded queries) |\n| Journal compressor | `snappy` (lower CPU overhead than `zlib` at comparable compression) |\n| Replica set write concern | Default write concern raised to `majority` |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Required Changes\n\n### 3.1 Disable SCRAM-SHA-1\n\n**Why:** SCRAM-SHA-1 is weaker than SCRAM-SHA-256. All current MongoDB 6.0 drivers\nsupport SHA-256; retaining SHA-1 is unnecessary attack surface.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Verify all application connection strings use drivers that support SCRAM-SHA-256.\n2. Set the `authenticationMechanisms` parameter to `SCRAM-SHA-256` only in\n   `mongod.conf`:\n   ```yaml\n   security:\n     authorization: enabled\n     keyFile: /etc/mongo-keyfile/keyfile\n     authenticationMechanisms: SCRAM-SHA-256\n   ```\n3. Re-roll the StatefulSet (one pod at a time, waiting for `SECONDARY` to catch up\n   before proceeding to the next) to pick up the new config.\n4. Re-provision the `admin-user` credential so MongoDB regenerates the stored keys\n   with SHA-256 only:\n   ```javascript\n   db.getSiblingDB(\"admin\").updateUser(\"admin-user\", {\n     mechanisms: [\"SCRAM-SHA-256\"],\n     pwd: \"<new-password>\"\n   });\n   ```\n\n### 3.2 Reduce `admin-user` to Least-Privilege Roles\n\n**Why:** A single account combining `clusterAdmin`, `userAdminAnyDatabase`, and\n`readWriteAnyDatabase` violates least privilege. A compromise of this credential\ngrants full cluster and data access simultaneously.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Create separate accounts for each function:\n   - `dba-cluster` → `clusterAdmin` only (for replica-set and sharding ops)\n   - `dba-users` → `userAdminAnyDatabase` only (for user management)\n   - Application service accounts → `readWrite` scoped to specific databases only\n2. Update Kubernetes Secrets and any application config referencing `admin-user`.\n3. Once all consumers have migrated, remove the broad roles from `admin-user` or\n   drop the account entirely.\n\n### 3.3 Enable TLS for All Connections\n\n**Why:** Without TLS, both client traffic and inter-member replication traffic are\nplaintext. The current keyFile provides mutual authentication between members but\nno encryption.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Issue a CA certificate and per-member certificates (one SAN per pod DNS name).\n   Store CA cert, member cert, and key as a Kubernetes Secret (e.g.,\n   `mongo-tls-certs`).\n2. Mount the Secret into each pod (new volume in the StatefulSet spec).\n3. Update `mongod.conf` in the `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   net:\n     tls:\n       mode: requireTLS\n       certificateKeyFile: /etc/mongo-tls/tls.pem\n       CAFile: /etc/mongo-tls/ca.crt\n   ```\n4. For inter-member (keyFile) auth, switch to x.509 internal authentication\n   (`security.clusterAuthMode: x509`) once TLS is in place, so the keyFile Secret\n   can be retired.\n5. Re-roll the StatefulSet member-by-member:\n   - Set `tlsMode: allowTLS` first (accepts both plain and TLS) → roll all three\n     pods → set `tlsMode: requireTLS` → roll again.\n   This two-phase roll avoids a split-brain during the transition.\n\n### 3.4 Restrict Network Binding\n\n**Why:** `bindIpAll: true` exposes mongod on every pod interface. Inside\nKubernetes the pod IP is sufficient; binding to all interfaces is unnecessary.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Replace `net.bindIpAll: true` with `net.bindIp: 127.0.0.1,${POD_IP}` in\n   `mongod.conf`. Inject `POD_IP` via a Downward API env var in the StatefulSet:\n   ```yaml\n   env:\n     - name: POD_IP\n       valueFrom:\n         fieldRef:\n           fieldPath: status.podIP\n   ```\n   Or use `$(POD_IP)` substitution if the startup command supports it; alternatively\n   set `bindIp` to `0.0.0.0` and rely on Kubernetes NetworkPolicy to restrict\n   access at the network layer.\n2. Apply a `NetworkPolicy` in the `mongodb` namespace that allows port 27017 only\n   from authorized application namespaces and denies all other ingress.\n\n### 3.5 Lower Log Verbosity to 0\n\n**Why:** `verbosity: 1` floods logs with internal debug messages, increasing\nstorage cost and making it harder to identify real warnings and errors in\nproduction.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Edit the `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   systemLog:\n     verbosity: 0\n   ```\n2. The change takes effect on pod restart. It can also be applied at runtime\n   without a restart using:\n   ```javascript\n   db.adminCommand({ setParameter: 1, logLevel: 0 });\n   ```\n   (apply on each member individually, including the primary)\n\n### 3.6 Tighten Slow-Operation Threshold to 50 ms\n\n**Why:** The current threshold of 200 ms misses operations in the 50–200 ms range\nthat are indicative of index-scan regressions or lock contention. A 50 ms\nthreshold provides earlier warning of degrading query performance.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Edit the `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   operationProfiling:\n     mode: slowOp\n     slowOpThresholdMs: 50\n   ```\n2. Can also be applied live without restart:\n   ```javascript\n   db.adminCommand({ setParameter: 1, slowOpThresholdMs: 50 });\n   ```\n   (apply on each member)\n3. Review the profiling collection (`db.system.profile`) after the change to\n   assess baseline query health before the threshold takes permanent effect.\n\n### 3.7 Migrate Journal Compressor from `zlib` to `snappy`\n\n**Why:** `zlib` offers good compression ratios but is CPU-intensive. `snappy`\nprovides significantly faster compression/decompression at a modest reduction in\nratio — a better trade-off for write-heavy OLTP workloads. If storage efficiency\nis the priority and CPU is available, `zlib` may be retained; `zstd` (available\nin MongoDB 4.2+) is a third option with better ratio than `snappy` and lower CPU\nthan `zlib`.\n\n**Warning:** WiredTiger compressor is a **storage-engine configuration** — it\napplies to new data written after the change. Existing data on disk is not\nrecompressed automatically. A full initial sync is required to recompress existing\ndata on each node.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Update `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   storage:\n     wiredTiger:\n       engineConfig:\n         journalCompressor: snappy\n   ```\n2. Roll the StatefulSet one pod at a time:\n   - Take a secondary offline (`priority: 0`, `votes: 0` in `rs.reconfig()`).\n   - Delete the pod's PVC data dir contents (or use a new PVC) and let it\n     perform an initial sync from a healthy member with the new compressor.\n   - Verify the member rejoins and reaches `SECONDARY` state.\n   - Repeat for the remaining secondary, then step down the primary and repeat.\n3. Revert `rs.reconfig()` changes to priority/votes after all members are updated.\n\n### 3.8 Raise Default Write Concern to `majority`\n\n**Why:** The current replica set default write concern is `{ w: 1, wtimeout: 0 }`,\nmeaning writes are acknowledged by the primary only before returning to the client.\nA majority write concern ensures data is durable on at least two of three members\nbefore acknowledgement, preventing data loss on primary failover.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n```javascript\ncfg = rs.conf();\ncfg.settings.getLastErrorDefaults = { w: \"majority\", wtimeout: 5000 };\nrs.reconfig(cfg);\n```\nAlternatively, set this in application connection strings\n(`?w=majority&wtimeoutMS=5000`) for per-connection control.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Execution Order and Dependencies\n\nThe changes must be sequenced to avoid outages:\n\n```\nStep 1  → 3.5 (lower verbosity) — live setParameter, zero downtime\nStep 2  → 3.6 (slow-op threshold) — live setParameter, zero downtime\nStep 3  → 3.4 (network binding + NetworkPolicy) — rolling pod restart\nStep 4  → 3.3 (TLS, phase 1: allowTLS) — rolling restart with new certs\nStep 5  → 3.1 (disable SCRAM-SHA-1) — requires TLS in place first\nStep 6  → 3.3 (TLS, phase 2: requireTLS) — rolling restart to enforce\nStep 7  → 3.2 (least-privilege users) — live user admin, no restart\nStep 8  → 3.8 (majority write concern) — live rs.reconfig(), no restart\nStep 9  → 3.7 (journal compressor) — full rolling initial-sync, planned window\n```\n\nSteps 1–2 are non-disruptive and can be performed as a dry run before the formal\nchange window. Steps 3–6 require coordinated rolling restarts. Step 9 is the most\ndisruptive and should be scheduled as a separate maintenance window.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Rollback Notes\n\n- **Config changes** (verbosity, threshold, compressor): revert the `mongod-config`\n  ConfigMap and re-roll the StatefulSet.\n- **TLS**: reverting from `requireTLS` → `allowTLS` → plain requires two rolling\n  restarts in reverse order; clients must also be reconfigured.\n- **Journal compressor**: once data is written with `snappy`, it cannot be read\n  by a mongod configured for `zlib` only. Ensure all members are updated before\n  writing new data, and maintain a backup before any storage-format change.\n- **User changes**: keep the old `admin-user` credential in the Secret until all\n  new service accounts are confirmed working in production.\n\n---\n\n*This document is for change-window planning only. The live cluster has not been modified.*\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":752,"cache_read_input_tokens":32910,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":752},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"899bbae7-b5e5-4c4d-898d-18e3a1b357c2","uuid":"84374412-0d05-4710-a76e-edfb280c3789","request_id":"req_011CcRG9TPXH7oDFknEu2fSS"}
