{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013tFkoTQWft2opSfPU2EgZh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_011eccsM4voRj9Q99gpxPEem","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/plan.md","content":"# MongoDB Replica Set — Change & Migration Plan\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-25  \n**Cluster namespace:** `mongodb`  \n**Replica set name:** `mongodb-replica`  \n**Status:** REVIEW ONLY — no changes applied to the live cluster.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current State Inventory\n\n### 1.1 Replica Set Topology\n\n| Member | Host | Priority | Votes | Arbiter | Hidden |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 0 | `mongodb-replica-0.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` | 1 | 1 | no | no |\n| 1 | `mongodb-replica-1.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` | 1 | 1 | no | no |\n| 2 | `mongodb-replica-2.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` | 1 | 1 | no | no |\n\n- Protocol version: 1 (Raft)\n- `writeConcernMajorityJournalDefault`: true\n- All three members are equal-priority data-bearing nodes; primary is elected by the set.\n- Default write concern: `{ w: 1, wtimeout: 0 }` (primary acknowledgement only).\n\n### 1.2 Users and Roles\n\n| User | DB | Roles |\n|---|---|---|\n| `admin-user` | `admin` | `clusterAdmin`, `userAdminAnyDatabase`, `readWriteAnyDatabase` |\n\n- Authentication mechanisms active: **SCRAM-SHA-1** and **SCRAM-SHA-256** (both enabled).\n- Password stored in Kubernetes Secret `admin-user-password`.\n\n### 1.3 Storage — Journal Compressor\n\nWiredTiger journal compressor: **`zlib`**  \n(set via `mongod-config` ConfigMap → `storage.wiredTiger.engineConfig.journalCompressor`)\n\n### 1.4 Log Verbosity\n\n`systemLog.verbosity: 1` — raised above the MongoDB default (`0`).  \nProduces extra diagnostic output for all components globally.\n\n### 1.5 Slow-Operation Threshold\n\n`operationProfiling.mode: slowOp`, `operationProfiling.slowOpThresholdMs: 200`  \nThe MongoDB default is 100 ms. The current value of 200 ms is less sensitive than\nthe default — operations completing between 100 ms and 200 ms are not flagged.\n\n### 1.6 Network Binding\n\n`net.bindIpAll: true` — mongod listens on all pod interfaces (0.0.0.0).\n\n### 1.7 TLS/SSL\n\nNot configured. Client-to-server and inter-member replication traffic are\nunencrypted. Internal member authentication relies on a shared `keyFile` Secret\n(`mongo-keyfile`), which provides mutual auth but no encryption in transit.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Target Hardened Baseline\n\n| Area | Current | Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Auth mechanisms | SCRAM-SHA-1 + SCRAM-SHA-256 | SCRAM-SHA-256 only |\n| Privilege model | One super-account with 3 broad roles | Least-privilege: one account per function |\n| TLS | None | `requireTLS` for clients and inter-member traffic |\n| Network binding | All interfaces (`0.0.0.0`) | Pod IP + loopback; NetworkPolicy for port 27017 |\n| Log verbosity | `1` | `0` (production default) |\n| Slow-op threshold | `200 ms` | `50 ms` (catch more degraded queries) |\n| Journal compressor | `zlib` | `snappy` (lower CPU overhead) |\n| Default write concern | `{ w: 1 }` | `{ w: \"majority\", wtimeout: 5000 }` |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Required Changes\n\n### 3.1 Disable SCRAM-SHA-1\n\n**Why:** SCRAM-SHA-1 is cryptographically weaker than SCRAM-SHA-256. All MongoDB 6.0\nclient drivers support SHA-256; retaining SHA-1 is unnecessary attack surface.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Confirm all application connection strings use drivers that support SCRAM-SHA-256.\n2. Update `mongod-config` ConfigMap to restrict accepted mechanisms:\n   ```yaml\n   security:\n     authorization: enabled\n     keyFile: /etc/mongo-keyfile/keyfile\n     authenticationMechanisms: SCRAM-SHA-256\n   ```\n3. Re-provision `admin-user` so MongoDB stores only SHA-256 credentials:\n   ```javascript\n   db.getSiblingDB(\"admin\").updateUser(\"admin-user\", {\n     mechanisms: [\"SCRAM-SHA-256\"],\n     pwd: \"<new-password>\"\n   });\n   ```\n4. Roll the StatefulSet one pod at a time (see Section 4 for order).\n\n### 3.2 Enforce Least-Privilege Roles\n\n**Why:** A single credential combining `clusterAdmin`, `userAdminAnyDatabase`, and\n`readWriteAnyDatabase` violates least privilege. Compromise of this one account\nyields full cluster control and unrestricted data access simultaneously.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Create separate purpose-scoped accounts:\n   - `dba-cluster` → `clusterAdmin` only (replica-set and sharding operations)\n   - `dba-users` → `userAdminAnyDatabase` only (user lifecycle management)\n   - Per-application service accounts → `readWrite` scoped to specific databases\n2. Update Kubernetes Secrets and application config to reference the new accounts.\n3. After verifying all consumers work, revoke the broad roles from `admin-user`\n   or drop the account entirely.\n\n### 3.3 Enable TLS for All Connections\n\n**Why:** Without TLS, client traffic and inter-member replication are plaintext.\nThe keyFile provides mutual authentication between members but no encryption.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Issue a CA certificate and per-member server certificates, one SAN per pod\n   DNS name (e.g., `mongodb-replica-0.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local`).\n   Store the CA cert, combined cert+key PEM, in a new Secret (e.g., `mongo-tls-certs`).\n2. Mount the Secret as a volume in the StatefulSet at `/etc/mongo-tls/`.\n3. Update `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   net:\n     tls:\n       mode: requireTLS\n       certificateKeyFile: /etc/mongo-tls/tls.pem\n       CAFile: /etc/mongo-tls/ca.crt\n   ```\n4. Two-phase rolling restart to avoid split-brain during transition:\n   - Phase 1: set `mode: allowTLS` → roll all three pods → confirm all SECONDARY.\n   - Phase 2: set `mode: requireTLS` → roll all three pods again.\n5. After TLS is enforced, optionally migrate internal auth from keyFile to x.509\n   (`security.clusterAuthMode: x509`) to retire the `mongo-keyfile` Secret.\n\n### 3.4 Restrict Network Binding\n\n**Why:** Binding to all interfaces exposes mongod unnecessarily. Inside Kubernetes\nthe pod IP is sufficient for service mesh and headless-service connectivity.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Replace `net.bindIpAll: true` with an explicit `net.bindIp` in `mongod-config`.\n   Inject the pod IP via a Downward API env var in the StatefulSet:\n   ```yaml\n   env:\n     - name: POD_IP\n       valueFrom:\n         fieldRef:\n           fieldPath: status.podIP\n   ```\n   Then in `mongod.conf`:\n   ```yaml\n   net:\n     bindIp: 127.0.0.1,$(POD_IP)\n   ```\n2. Apply a `NetworkPolicy` in the `mongodb` namespace allowing ingress on port\n   27017 only from authorized application namespaces; deny all other ingress.\n\n### 3.5 Lower Log Verbosity to 0\n\n**Why:** `verbosity: 1` floods logs with internal debug output, inflating storage\ncosts and burying real warnings and errors.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Edit `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   systemLog:\n     verbosity: 0\n   ```\n2. Can also be applied live without pod restart (on each member):\n   ```javascript\n   db.adminCommand({ setParameter: 1, logLevel: 0 });\n   ```\n\n### 3.6 Tighten Slow-Operation Threshold to 50 ms\n\n**Why:** At 200 ms, queries degrading into the 50–200 ms range — a common early\nindicator of missing indexes or lock contention — go undetected. A 50 ms threshold\ngives earlier warning.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Edit `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   operationProfiling:\n     mode: slowOp\n     slowOpThresholdMs: 50\n   ```\n2. Can also be applied live (on each member):\n   ```javascript\n   db.adminCommand({ setParameter: 1, slowOpThresholdMs: 50 });\n   ```\n3. After applying, review `db.system.profile` to gauge baseline query health\n   before committing the tighter threshold permanently.\n\n### 3.7 Migrate Journal Compressor from `zlib` to `snappy`\n\n**Why:** `zlib` is CPU-intensive. `snappy` decompresses ~5× faster at a modest\nreduction in compression ratio — a better trade-off for write-heavy OLTP workloads.\n(`zstd` is a valid third option: better ratio than snappy, lower CPU than zlib,\navailable in MongoDB 4.2+.)\n\n**Warning:** WiredTiger's compressor is a storage-engine setting. Existing on-disk\ndata is not recompressed on config change — new blocks written after the restart\nuse the new compressor. A full initial sync is required on each member to\nrecompress all data uniformly.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n1. Update `mongod-config` ConfigMap:\n   ```yaml\n   storage:\n     wiredTiger:\n       engineConfig:\n         journalCompressor: snappy\n   ```\n2. Roll each member through a fresh initial sync:\n   - Temporarily set `priority: 0, votes: 0` for the target member via\n     `rs.reconfig()` to isolate it.\n   - Delete the pod; let it rejoin and perform an initial sync from a healthy\n     member that already has the new compressor config.\n   - Verify member reaches `SECONDARY` before proceeding to the next.\n   - Repeat for the remaining secondary, then step down the primary and repeat.\n3. Restore original `priority` and `votes` values via `rs.reconfig()` when done.\n\n### 3.8 Raise Default Write Concern to `majority`\n\n**Why:** The current default `{ w: 1, wtimeout: 0 }` acknowledges writes from the\nprimary alone. On primary failover, in-flight writes that reached only the primary\nare lost. `w: majority` ensures data is durable on at least 2 of 3 members before\nthe client receives acknowledgement.\n\n**Steps (do not apply now):**\n```javascript\ncfg = rs.conf();\ncfg.settings.getLastErrorDefaults = { w: \"majority\", wtimeout: 5000 };\nrs.reconfig(cfg);\n```\nAlternatively, enforce majority durability at the application layer via connection\nstring parameters (`?w=majority&wtimeoutMS=5000`).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Execution Order and Dependencies\n\nChanges must be sequenced to avoid outages or inconsistent intermediate states:\n\n| Step | Change | Method | Downtime |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Lower log verbosity (3.5) | Live `setParameter` per member | None |\n| 2 | Tighten slow-op threshold (3.6) | Live `setParameter` per member | None |\n| 3 | Restrict network binding + NetworkPolicy (3.4) | Rolling pod restart | None (rolling) |\n| 4 | TLS phase 1: `allowTLS` (3.3) | Rolling restart with cert mounts | None (rolling) |\n| 5 | Disable SCRAM-SHA-1 (3.1) | Config + user update, rolling restart | None (rolling) |\n| 6 | TLS phase 2: `requireTLS` (3.3) | Rolling restart | None (rolling) |\n| 7 | Least-privilege users (3.2) | Live user admin | None |\n| 8 | Majority write concern (3.8) | Live `rs.reconfig()` | None |\n| 9 | Journal compressor migration (3.7) | Full rolling initial sync | None (rolling, slow) |\n\nSteps 1–2 are non-disruptive and can serve as a low-risk warm-up before the\nformal change window. Step 9 is the most time-consuming and should be scheduled\nas a separate maintenance window with a storage backup in hand.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Rollback Notes\n\n- **Config changes (verbosity, threshold):** revert `mongod-config` ConfigMap and\n  restart affected pods; or apply live via `setParameter` in reverse.\n- **TLS:** revert `requireTLS` → `allowTLS` → remove `net.tls` block, two rolling\n  restarts. Client applications must also remove TLS connection config.\n- **Journal compressor:** once a member has written blocks with `snappy`, those\n  blocks cannot be read by a `zlib`-only mongod. Ensure all members complete the\n  initial sync before writing new application data under the new compressor. Keep\n  a volume snapshot or `mongodump` backup before starting Step 9.\n- **User changes:** preserve the original `admin-user` Secret until all new\n  service accounts are confirmed working in production.\n\n---\n\n*This document is for change-window planning only. The live cluster has not been modified.*\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":150,"cache_read_input_tokens":39254,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":150},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"899bbae7-b5e5-4c4d-898d-18e3a1b357c2","uuid":"fc02a000-378b-4129-b624-c47bf9676ade","request_id":"req_011CcRGGiUZxeLB9Lr4g4fSB"}
